{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17585046","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17585046"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T08:01:29+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T08:01:29+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14843"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"14843","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/14843"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.1,0.1,0.1,0.58,0.1]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7534"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58956"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"7534","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/7534"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14843"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44367"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"74"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4943"},{"type":"tags","id":"4950"},{"type":"tags","id":"5090"},{"type":"tags","id":"7879"},{"type":"tags","id":"7881"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"18436"},{"type":"contributions","id":"18571"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58956","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/58956"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003E\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following components is found in cryoprecipitate?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Factor V","Factor VII","Thrombin","von Willebrand factor","Prothrombin"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ECryoprecipitate is a blood product derived from fresh frozen plasma that is rich in specific coagulation factors. It is prepared by thawing fresh frozen plasma at 1-6\u00b0C and collecting the precipitate that forms. It is primarily used to treat hypofibrinogenaemia (fibrinogen \u0026lt;1.5 g/L) and von Willebrand disease, as well as in massive transfusion protocols.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003Evon Willebrand factor\u003C/strong\u003E is one of the main components found in cryoprecipitate, along with fibrinogen, factor VIII, factor XIII, and fibronectin. These proteins precipitate out when fresh frozen plasma is thawed at 1-6\u00b0C.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFactor V\u003C/strong\u003E remains primarily in the supernatant during cryoprecipitate preparation and is therefore not concentrated in the final product. It is found in fresh frozen plasma.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EFactor VII\u003C/strong\u003E is a vitamin K-dependent clotting factor that is not concentrated in cryoprecipitate. It is present in fresh frozen plasma and prothrombin complex concentrate.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EThrombin\u003C/strong\u003E is not present in cryoprecipitate as it is an activated form of prothrombin. Adding thrombin would cause the formation of fibrin clots within the blood product.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProthrombin\u003C/strong\u003E is another vitamin K-dependent clotting factor that is not concentrated in cryoprecipitate. Like factor VII, it is found in fresh frozen plasma and prothrombin complex concentrate.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Cryoprecipitate contains fibrinogen, von Willebrand factor, factor VIII, factor XIII, and fibronectin.","Cryoprecipitate is produced by thawing fresh frozen plasma at 1-6\u00b0C and collecting the precipitate.","Cryoprecipitate is primarily used to treat hypofibrinogenaemia and von Willebrand disease."],"references":["Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., Fausto, N., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (2014). Robbins and Cotran pathologic basis of disease, professional edition e-book. Elsevier health sciences","National Clinical Guideline Centre (UK). Blood Transfusion. London: National Institute for Health and Care Excellence (NICE); 2015 Nov. (NICE Guideline, No. 24.) 16, Cryoprecipitate: thresholds and targets. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK338779/","Callum JL, Karkouti K, Lin Y. Cryoprecipitate: the current state of knowledge. Transfus Med Rev. 2009 Jul;23(3):177-88. doi: 10.1016/j.tmrv.2009.03.001. PMID: 19539873.","Nascimento B, Goodnough LT, Levy JH. Cryoprecipitate therapy. Br J Anaesth. 2014 Dec;113(6):922-34. doi: 10.1093/bja/aeu158. Epub 2014 Jun 27. PMID: 24972790; PMCID: PMC4627369."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44367"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"14843"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"44367","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/44367"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-03T23:07:07+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-05T19:40:29+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7534"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"58956"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"71","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/71"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Junior","synonyms":null,"description":"Suitable for a junior, pre-clinical medical student","position":0,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"74","links":{"self":"https://ap